Ebola test positive for New York doctor who treated patients in Africa
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A physician with Doctors Without Borders [MSF] who returned to New York City after treating Ebola victims in West Africa tested positive for the virus, setting off fresh fears about the spread of the disease. Dr. CS, 33, is in isolation at Bellevue Hospital and officials sought to reassure the public that they are safe from Ebola, New York Mayor Bill de Blasio said at a news conference. CS developed a fever and gastrointestinal symptoms after working for the humanitarian organization in Guinea, one of 3 West African nations hardest hit by Ebola.

A specially trained team wearing protective gear transported him to Bellevue Hospital from his Manhattan apartment earlier on Thu [23 Oct 2014], the city said in a statement. Governor Andrew Cuomo said CG had been in direct contact with 4 people, and health authorities had quarantined 3 friends [including his fiancee, in hospital]. The 4th person, a taxi driver, was determined not to be at risk of Ebola.

There have been 9 cases of Ebola seen in the United States since the beginning of August [2014].

CS's Facebook page, which included a photo of him clad in protective gear, said he went to Guinea around 18 Sep [2014] and then flew to Brussels on 16 Oct [2014]. He has specialized in international emergency medicine at Columbia University-New York Presbyterian Hospital in New York City since 2011. Columbia in a statement said he has not been to work nor seen any patients... [His] apartment in Manhattan's Harlem neighborhood was sealed off on Thursday [23 Oct 2014] but the rest of the 6-story brick building had remained open to residents, health officials said... - more

[By Ellen Wulfhorst]

